ck special for ''My Life''\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Further|List of awards and nominations received by Rain }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rain (vocalist)|Rain}}\n* {{Official website|http://raincompany.co.kr/home.php}}\n* [http://mnet.interest.me/tv/vod/159311 Rain Effect reality show official website] {{in lang|ko}}\n* [http://musictea.org/music/%EB%B9%84 Rain] discography at MusicTea\n* {{IMDb name|1955294|Rain}}\n* {{Kmdb person|00042185}}\n* {{HanCinema person}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw&ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[KBS Song Festival]]'' \u2013 Best New Artist|years=2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seven (South Korean singer)|Se7en]]|year=2003}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=SBS Music Awards \u2013 Best New Artist|years=2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seven (South Korean singer)|Se7en]]|year=2003}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mnet Asian Music Awards|4th Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2013 Best New Artist|years=2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Seven (South Korean singer)|Se7en]]|year=2003}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Golden Disk Awards|17th Golden Disk Awards]] \u2013 Best New Artist|years=2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Big Mama (group)|Big Mama]]|year=2003}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mnet Asian Music Awards|6th Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2013 Artist of the Year|years=2004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[TVXQ]]|year=2005}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mnet Asian Music Awards|6th Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2013 Album of the Year|years=2004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[SG Wannabe]]|years=2005}}\n{{s-bef|before=Incumbent}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mnet Asian Music Awards|6th Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2013 Song of the Year|years=2004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[SG Wannabe]]|years=2006}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Hyori]]|year=2008}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mnet Asian Music Awards|10th Mnet Asian Music Awards]] \u2013 Best Dance Music|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hyuna]]|years=2011}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Rain}}\n{{Rain singles}}\n{{Cube Entertainment}}\n{{JYP Entertainment}}\n{{Golden Disk Awards for New Artist of the Year}}\n{{Paeksang Arts Award Best New Actor Film}}\n{{Baeksang Arts Award for Most Popular Actor Television}}\n{{Forbes Korea Power Celebrity}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rain}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean male actors]]\n[[Category:Cube Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Dankook University alumni]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from South Korea]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:J. Tune Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:JYP Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Mnet Asian Music Award winners]]\n[[Category:South Korean expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Korean male film actors]]\n[[Category:South Korean male idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean male singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean male television actors]]\n[[Category:South Korean military personnel]]\n[[Category:South Korean music industry executives]]\n[[Category:South Korean pop singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean record producers]]\n[[Category:South Korean rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:South Korean singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century South Korean singers]]\n[[Category:Anyang Arts High School alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean singer and actor}}\n{{Korean name|Jung}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name                = Rain\n| image               = 140120 \ud53c \ub053\ub294 \uccad\ucd98 vip\uc2dc\uc0ac\ud68c-\ube44.jpg\n| caption             = Rain in 2014\n| native_name         = \ube44 \n| birth_name          = Jung Ji-hoon\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1982|6|25}}<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=April 29, 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Seosan]], [[South Chungcheong]] Province, [[South Korea]]\n| residence           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* dancer\n* record producer\n* actor}}\n| years_active        = 1998\u20132000; 2002\u2013present\n| height              = \n| spouse              = {{Marriage|[[Kim Tae-hee]]|January 19, 2017}}\n| children            = 2\n| module              = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n*[[K-pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| instrument          = {{flatlist| \n* Vocals\n* piano\n* guitar}}\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n*[[JYP Entertainment|JYP]]\n*[[J. Tune Entertainment|J. Tune]]\n*[[William Morris Endeavor|WME]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/top-star-rain-joins-wma-12540.html|title=Top Star Rain Joins WMA|date=February 12, 2008|website=KBS World}}</ref>\n*[[Cube Entertainment|Cube]]\n*R.A.I.N. Company}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n*FanClub<ref name=\"boyband\">{{cite web|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=6651319|title=\ube44, 16\uc138 \ub2f9\uc2dc \ud32c\ud074\ub7fd \ud65c\ub3d9 \uacfc\uac70\uc0ac\uc9c4 \uacf5\uac1c \u2018\ub9d0\ub77c\uae7d\uc774\uc600\ub124\u2019Rain, released the picture when he was in 'Fan Club'|date=November 12, 2011|website=Ilgan Sports|language=Korean}}</ref> \n*[[MBLAQ]]\n*[[Park Jin-young|JYP]]\n*[[JYP Nation]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|http://raincompany.co.kr}}(Korean)<br/>{{URL|http://www.rain-jungjihoon.jp/}}(Japanese)\n| alias               = Bi\n}}\n| religion     = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| background = solo_singer\n| hangul      = {{linktext|\uc815|\uc9c0|\ud6c8}}\n| hanja       = \n| rr          = Jeong Ji-hun\n| mr          = Ch\u014fng Chihun\n| hangulstage = {{linktext|\ube44}}\n| rrstage     = Bi\n| mrstage     = Pi\n}}\n'''Jung Ji-hoon''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc815\uc9c0\ud6c8}}, born June 25, 1982), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Rain''' (Korean \ube44 IPA ['pi\u02d0]), is a South Korean singer-songwriter, actor, and music producer.\n\nRain's musical career includes seven albums (six Korean, one Japanese), 28 singles and numerous concert tours around the world. He achieved breakthrough success with his third Korean album, ''[[It's Raining (album)|It's Raining]]'' (2004), which spawned the [[It's Raining (Rain song)|number one single of the same name]]. The album sold a million copies in Asia, and established Rain as an international star.\n\nRain made his acting debut in the 2003 drama ''[[Sang Doo! Let's Go To School]]''. His lead role in the pan-Asia hit drama ''[[Full House (2004 TV series)|Full House]]'' (2004) established his status as a Hallyu star. In 2008, Rain made his Hollywood debut in the film ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]'' and starred in ''[[Ninja Assassin]]'' (2009), the latter of which made him the first Korean to win an [[MTV]] award.\n\nIn 2015, Rain set up his own company, R.A.I.N. Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://imnews.imbc.com/replay/2015/nwtoday/article/3788078_17828.html|script-title=ko:[\uc5f0\uc608\ud22c\ub370\uc774] \uac00\uc218 \ube44, 1\uc778 \uae30\ud68d\uc0ac '\ub808\uc778\ucef4\ud37c\ub2c8' \uc124\ub9bd|last=\ub9ac\ud3ec\ud130|first=\uae40\uc774\uc120|website=iMBC|language=ko|access-date=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRain was born as Jung Ji-hoon on June 25, 1982, in [[Seosan]], South Korea. His mother died in December 2000 as she struggled with diabetes. In the same year, Rain was recruited as a trainee for [[JYP Entertainment]], led by recording artist and producer [[Park Jin-young]]. In a [[CNN]] interview and also in a [[Discovery Channel]] documentary called ''Discovering Hip Korea'',<ref>{{cite web|author=Hong Gil-dong  |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20081223000075 |title=BRIEFLY \u2013 Discovery to air film on Seoul |website=[[The Korea Herald]] |date=April 4, 2010 |accessdate=}}</ref> he recalled being repeatedly rejected because of his looks: \"In fact, I was told after one audition that my singing and dancing was great but I did not make it because I did not have [[Asian blepharoplasty|double eyelids]].\" He was eventually recruited into JYP Entertainment, as Park Jin-young saw his drive and persistence. During his early years of training, Rain was a backup dancer.<ref name=\"multiple\">{{cite news | title=Pop star Rain (Bi), reaching out beyond Asia| url =https://www.hancinema.net/pop-star-rain-bi%E2%80%93reaching-out-beyond-asia-4304.html | work =Hancinema|publisher=KBS Global | date = October 26, 2005 }}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n=== 1998\u20132000: Debut in boy band Fanclub ===\nRain, aged 16, debuted as a member of a boy band named Fanclub (\ud32c\ud074\ub7fd).<ref name=\"boyband\" /> Despite releasing two albums, the group failed to be commercially successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.naver.com/album/index.nhn?albumId=64948|title=Fanclub|publisher=Naver Music|accessdate=February 5, 2014|language=Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arirang.co.kr/TV2/Star_Focus.asp?F_KEY=886&sys_lang=Kor&Nowpage=1|script-title=ko:\ube44|publisher=Arirang|accessdate=February 5, 2014|language=Korean}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u201306: Debut as solo singer and Pan-Asia success===\nIn 2002, Jung debuted as a solo singer with his first solo album titled ''[[Bad Guy (album)|Bad Guy]]'' where he was introduced to the media through his stage name, Rain. Two singles were released from the album - the eponymous title track \"Bad Guy\" and \"Handshake\".  Following the success of his debut, Rain released his second album, ''[[Rain 2]]'' with the lead single \"[[Ways to Avoid the Sun]]\".<ref name=success>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-gets-ready-to-pour-it-on-3129.html|title=\nRain Gets Ready to Pour It On|date=June 14, 2005|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> From 2002-2003, he became a host for [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]'s ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]''.\n\nRain then released his third album, ''[[It's Raining (album)|It's Raining]]'', which topped music charts in Korea as well as throughout Asia. To promote the release, Rain then embarked on his first tour, ''[[Rainy Day 2005 Tour]]'', which spanned a total of 14 concerts in 8 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2005/10/13/2005101361017.html|title=\nRain Season Breaks Records Across Asia|date=October 13, 2005|website=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]}}</ref> The album went on to sell over a million copies in Asia,<ref>{{cite news| title=Rain\u2019s album records sales of over one million copies in Asia| url=http://english.kbs.co.kr/entertainment/news/1375194_11858.html| work=KBS Global| accessdate=February 18, 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070126072537/http://english.kbs.co.kr/entertainment/news/1375194_11858.html| archivedate=January 26, 2007| df=mdy-all}}</ref> cementing Rain's position as one of the region's top musical acts.\n\n===2006\u201307: Expansion outside Korea===\n\n[[File:Bi (Rain).jpg|thumb|Rain during a performance.|left|268x268px]]\n\n====Asia====\n[[File:Rain Korean Singer.JPG|thumb|Rain in Bangkok 2007|268x268px]]\nRain released his first Japanese album, ''[[Eternal Rain]]'' on September 13, 2006. He held his first Japanese solo concert, ''Rainy Day Japan''. This was followed up by the release of his fourth album, ''[[Rain's World]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2006/10/04/2006100461008.html|title=Rain Vows to Take the World by Storm|date=October 4, 2006|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> which also sold over a million copies in Asia and further established him as one of the top musical acts in Southeast Asia. The success of the album lead to a repackage album, which was released 2 months later.\n\nThe ''[[Rain's Coming World Tour]]'' began on December 15, 2006 at [[Seoul Olympic Stadium]] in Seoul<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-to-launch-world-tour-in-december-7163.html|title=Rain to Launch World Tour in December|date=September 13, 2006|work=KBS World}}</ref> and was scheduled to continue through 2007 to various parts of Asia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-to-tour-asia-6005.html|title=Rain to Tour Asia|date=May 11, 2016|website=KBS World}}</ref> [[Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/04/12/2007041261011.html|title=Singer Rain Descends on Australia for World Tour|date=April 12, 2007|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> [[United States]], and [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-s-world-tour-to-gross-w106-bln-7399.html|title=Rain's World Tour to Gross W106 Bln|date=October 12, 2006|website=KBS World}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2007, Rain became the first Korean star to perform at the [[Tokyo Dome]]. The concert seated nearly 55,000 attendees.<ref>{{cite news | first=C.R.A. | last=Garcia | title=Rain Becomes First K-Pop Star to Perform at Tokyo Dome | date=May 27, 2007 |website=The Korea Times| url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2007/07/201_3621.html| work= | pages = | accessdate = July 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Rain left [[JYP Entertainment]] to start his own company, [[J. Tune Entertainment]], but still retains his collaborative relationship with Park Jin-young.\n\n====United States====\nIn April 2006, Rain was mentioned by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine which listed him as one of the \"100 Most Influential People Who Shape Our World\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news | first=Bryan | last=Walsh | title=The People Who Shape Our World | date=May 8, 2006 | publisher= | url =http://www.time.com/time/archive/preview/0,10987,1187264,00.html | work =Time Magazine | pages = | accessdate = February 18, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | title=The TIME 100 | year=2006 | publisher= | url =http://www.time.com/time/2006/time100/ | work =Time Magazine | pages = | accessdate = February 18, 2007 }}</ref>  In 2007, Rain topped ''Time'' Magazine's online user poll, defeating [[Stephen Colbert]] by 100,000 votes;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100walkup/article/0,28804,1611030_1612457,00.html|title=Your Time 100|work=Time Magazine|date= April 19, 2007|accessdate= May 9, 2007}}</ref> Colbert jokingly retaliated by producing a parody of Rain's music video for \"Ways to Avoid the Sun\" called \"He's Singin' In Korean\", and challenged Rain to a dance-off or a \"cuddle-off\", or a \"spoon-off\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/u-s-comedian-rains-mockery-on-rain-9493.html|title=U.S. Comedian Rains Mockery on Rain|date=May 14, 2007|website=Chosun}}</ref> On May 5, 2008, Rain appeared in a surprise guest segment at the end of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'', and proceeded to engage Colbert in a dance-off on a [[Dance Dance Revolution]] machine.<ref name=\"Episode #04060\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?videoId=156555&display=all |title=Rain Dance-Off |date=May 5, 2008 |work=Colbert Report |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510065745/http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?videoId=156555&display=all |archivedate=May 10, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | title=The TIME 100 | publisher= | url= http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100walkup/article/0,28804,1611030_1612457,00.html | work =Time Magazine | pages = | accessdate = June 8, 2007 | date=April 20, 2007}}</ref> He also made it into ''[[People (magazine)|People's]]'' 2007 list of the \"Most Beautiful People\" in the world.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | title=All about the Beautiful people | date=April 26, 2007 | publisher=Daily Telegraph | url =http://www.news.com.au/sundaytelegraph/story/0,,21624419-5001021,00.html | work =Daily Telegraph | pages = | accessdate = April 29, 2007 }}</ref> In a press release, Rain stated that he was honored to be on the list, and also noted that it will be a great boost to his efforts to raise his public awareness in the United States.<ref name=\"Yahoo Canada\">{{cite news | title=SKorean pop star Rain listed in People's 100 Most Beautiful | date=April 30, 2007 | publisher=Yahoo Canada | url=http://ca.entertainment.yahoo.com/s/27042007/24/entertainment-news-skorean-pop-star-rain-listed-people-s-100-most.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502083141/http://ca.entertainment.yahoo.com/s/27042007/24/entertainment-news-skorean-pop-star-rain-listed-people-s-100-most.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=May 2, 2007 | work=Yahoo Canada | accessdate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nRain's concerts in the United States were also well received. His two-day concert, ''[[Rainy Day 2005 Tour|Rainy Day New York]]'', held at the [[Madison Square Garden]], were sold out within a matter of days. The concert was marketed and promoted by the Asian concert production company Rainstone Live.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rain's Sold-Out New York Gig Could Take K-Pop Global |date=February 3, 2006 |url=http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200602/200602030011.html |work=The Chosun Ilbo |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204104741/http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200602/200602030011.html |archivedate=February 4, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/27/arts/a-strong-forecast-for-korean-pops-rain.html|title=A strong forecast for Korean pop's Rain|date=January 27, 2006|website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>Esther Kim Lee -Seven Contemporary Plays from the Korean Diaspora in the Americas \u2013 Page xv 2012 \"For example, the singer Rain performed in Madison Square Garden to sold-out audiences, and South Korean television soap operas have inspired women in Southeast Asia to undergo cosmetic surgery to look \"Korean.\" \"</ref> Rain also performed two concert dates in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] on December 23\u201324, 2006; held at [[The Colosseum at Caesars Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2006/10/27/2006102761002.html|title=Rain Storms Coming to Las Vegas This Christmas|date=October 26, 2007|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\n===2008\u201312: Olympics, ''Rainism, Back to the Basic'' and continued popularity===\n[[File:RainF1.JPG|thumb|Rain at Sepang International Circuit F1 2011 post-party concert, Malaysia|left|268x268px]]\nIn January 2008, Rain was tapped to sing the theme song of the 2008 Beijing Olympic Games, \"Hand in Hand\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2008/01/16/2008011661018.html|title=Rain to Sing Theme for Beijing Olympics|date=January 16, 2008|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> He also performed at the Beijing Olympic closing ceremony in August, singing the closing theme song \u201cBeijing, Beijing, I Love Beijing\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2008/08/26/2008082661017.html|title=Rain Drinks In Olympics Emotion|date=August 26, 2008|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2008, Rain released his fifth Korean album, ''[[Rainism]]'', which spawned the number one hit single \"Love Story\". The music video for \"Love Story\" featured Korean actress [[Ha Ji-won]]. A second single, titled \"Rainism\", was subsequently released. Rain held a comeback showcase for the album, and appeared in a two-day special program where exclusive footage and interviews of the singer was shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/10/398_32272.html|title=It Will Be Raining Again in Korea|date=October 7, 2008|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/10/398_32517.html|title=Rain Finally Unveiled in Asia|date=October 12, 2008|website=The Korea Times}}</ref>\nOn November 24, 2008, the Commission of Youth Protection deemed the album inappropriate for people under 19 years old because the lyrics in the song \"Rainism\" were considered problematic due to their phallic and sexual references.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/11/117_35041.html|title=Ban on Rains Song Sizzles Show Biz|date=November 25, 2008|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> Rain re-released a \"clean version\" of \"Rainism\" shortly after, but instead of changing the original album's contents, a sticker was placed on the album that prohibited its sale to those under 19 years old.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asiatoday.co.kr/view.php?key=184448|script-title=ko:'\ub808\uc774\ub2c8\uc998' \ud074\ub9b0\ubc84\uc804\uc5d0 '\ub9e4\uc9c1 \uc2a4\ud2f1' \ube60\uc9c0\ub098|trans-title=Is 'magic stick' deleted in 'rainism' clean version?|date=November 25, 2008|newspaper=Asia today|language=Korean}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, in support of his fifth album ''Rainism'', Rain kicked off his Asian tour, ''[[The Legend of Rainism Asia Tour|The Legend of Rainism Tour]]'' with two shows at [[Olympic Gymnastics Arena]] in Seoul on October 9 and 10.<ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20091002000060 \"Event Calendar: October 2009\"] ''The Korea Herald''. October 2, 2009. Retrieved April 10, 2012</ref> It continued with concerts in various parts of Asia and concluded at [[The Colosseum at Caesars Palace]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], on December 24\u201325, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/08/201_50908.html|title=Rain Starts Asian Tour in Japan; in Seoul in Oct.|date=August 30, 2009|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2913370|title=Rain takes his act to Indonesia|date=December 3, 2009|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2010, Rain released a special mini-album titled ''[[Back to the Basic]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2010/04/398_63709.html|title=Rain Returns With Back to the Basic|date=April 6, 2010|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> including the singles \"Love Song\" starring [[Han Ye-seul]] in the music video<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/han-ye-seul-stars-in-new-rain-music-video-22694.html|title=Han Ye-seul stars in new Rain music video|date=March 24, 2010|website=10Asia}}</ref> as well as \"Hip Song\". Once again, Rain topped ''Time'' Magazine's TIME 100 poll.<ref>{{cite news|last=Megan|first=Friedman|title=Korean Pop Star Rain Wins TIME 100 Poll \u2013 Again|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/04/15/korean-pop-star-rain-wins-time-100-poll-again/|newspaper=Time Magazine|date=April 15, 2011}}</ref> In October, Rain represented Korea and performed at the [[Asia Song Festival|7th Asia Song Festival]], organised by Korea Foundation for International Culture Exchange, at the [[Seoul Olympic Stadium]].<ref>[http://english.kofice.or.kr/d40_asia/d40_asia_02_2010y.asp \"7th Asia Song Festival\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612015209/http://english.kofice.or.kr/d40_asia/d40_asia_02_2010y.asp |date=June 12, 2011 }} ''KOFICE''. October 23, 2010. Retrieved October 12, 2011</ref>\n\nThe following year, Rain made his third appearance in the TIME 100 poll. ''Time'' describes his win as \"The South Korean pop star turned actor Rain, 28, took the top spot in the TIME 100 reader poll for the third year, trouncing competitors from Barack Obama to Lady Gaga. That's pretty impressive online power for a guy whose main claim to Western fame is a role in the 2009 film Ninja Assassin.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The 2011 TIME 100, Rain |website=Time Magazine|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066482,00.html}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the ''Time'' honor, Rain went on a farewell tour, ''The Best Show Tour'', before his 21-month compulsory military service.<ref>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2011/09/23/0200000000AEN20110923007900315.HTML \"Top K-pop star Rain to join Army\"] ''Yonhap News Agency''. September 23, 2011.</ref> The tour spanned Southeast Asia including his first tour dates throughout South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2941912|title=Rain wraps his final concert tour|date=September 26, 2011|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> His last concert, ''Rain: Last of The Best'' was deemed as the best event in Gangnam District for 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2946489|title=Singer Rain\u2019s performance was deemed the best event in Gangnam District for 2011|date=January 2, 2012|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: CUBE Entertainment and ''Rain Effect''===\n[[File:Rain US military concert.JPG|thumb|Rain performs at a K-pop concert at [[Kunsan Air Base]] in September 2012]]\nOn September 17, it was officially announced that Rain signed with [[Cube Entertainment#Cube DC|Cube DC]], a sub-label of Cube Entertainment After signing with Cube DC, it was announced Rain would be going on his first tour since his discharge. The ''2013 Zepp Tour: Story of Rain'' saw Rain perform 10 dates in four cities in [[Japan]] over a few dates in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/74366|title=Rain to Tell Japanese Fans \"Story of Rain\" Next Month|date=October 8, 2013|website=10Asia}}</ref> In October, Rain held his first fan meeting since his discharge in Seoul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2978762|title=Rain meets with 3,000 fans|date=October 14, 2013|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\nAs a precursor to his new album, Rain starred in a reality show ''Rain Effect'', which premiered on December 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2981875|title=Rain\u2019s reality TV show to debut Dec. 19|date=December 12, 2013|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> The new album, titled ''[[Rain Effect]]'', was released on January 2, 2014 with music videos for double title tracks, \"30 Sexy\" and \"La Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/5862358/rain-makes-grand-return-with-sixth-album-rain-effect|title=Rain Makes Grand Return With Sixth Album 'Rain Effect'|date=January 7, 2004|website=Billboard}}</ref> A few months later, Rain released a repckaged version of the album, featuring the ballad single \"I Love You\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2984424|title=Rain repackages new album|date=February 5, 2014|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u2013present: R.A.I.N. Company, The Squall tour and My Life===\nOn September 7, 2015, Rain announced through his Facebook page that he and the CEO had come to a mutual decision to not renew his contract with [[Cube Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201509071124390461593_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Rain to leave Cube Entertainment|date=September 7, 2015|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> On October 11, he announced through his official website that he had created his own one-man agency with the aid of his longtime manager and other entertainment figures.<ref name=\"The Korean Times\">{{cite web |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/10/201_188392.html |title=Rain launches entertainment company |date=October 11, 2015 |work=The Korea Times|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom late 2015 to 2016, Rain embarked on his second world tour, titled ''[[The Squall World Tour|The Squall]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/11/06/2015110601425.html?related_all|title=Rain to Return to Concert Stage After 4-Year Break|date=November 6, 2015|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2015/11/03/0200000000AEN20151103001700315.html|title=Rain to launch world tour this week|date=November 3, 2015|website=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2016, R.A.I.N. Company announced that Rain would release a new album in 2017 with a series of promotional activities to accompany his musical comeback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/110861/rain-to-make-a-comeback-in-january-all-kpop-news|title=Rain to Make a Comeback in January|last=Min|first=Susan|date=December 12, 2016|website=MWave|publisher=|access-date=December 15, 2016}}</ref> He released the single \"The Best Present\", produced by [[Psy]] on January 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7655441/rain-psy-the-best-present-song-video|title=Rain Drops His Psy-Produced Single 'The Best Present,' An Ode to Fiancee Kim Tae Hee|date=January 17, 2017|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Rain appeared as a mentor on KBS' survival audition program, ''[[The Unit: Idol Rebooting Project|The Unit]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201710291748592801372_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Why did Rain decide to appear on audition show?|date=October 29, 2017|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, it was announced that Rain would come back with a new mini-album in December<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201710261807180689420_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Rain to release new album in December|date=October 26, 2017|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> with a comeback special titled ''2017 Rain is Back'' airing December 3 on KBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201711131646324509708_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Rain to air comeback special broadcast|date=November 13, 2017|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref> The comeback special was followed by a series of variety and music show promotional activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=076&aid=0003171137|script-title=ko:[\uacf5\uc2dd] \ube44 \uce21 \"'\ubb49\ub72c' \uac8c\uc2a4\ud2b8 \ucd9c\uc5f0, 11\uc6d4 6\uc77c \ub300\ub9cc \ucd9c\uad6d\"|access-date=November 29, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> Rain's album, ''[[My Life (Rain album)|My Life]]'' was released on December 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201712031333148030918_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Rain says still looking for challenges in \u2018Act 2\u2019 of life|date=December 3, 2017|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n\n=== 2003\u201306: Acting debut and Hallyu fame ===\nRain made his television debut in the [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] drama, ''[[Sang Doo! Let's Go To School]]'' (2003).<ref name=success /> The drama achieved good ratings and he won the Most Popular TV Actor award at the 2004 [[Baeksang Arts Awards]].\n\nIn 2004, Rain's popularity continued to climb when starred alongside [[Song Hye-kyo]] in the hit romantic comedy series ''[[Full House (Korean drama)|Full House]]'', which drew solid viewership ratings nationwide throughout its run with a peak viewer rating of 42.7 percent.<ref name=\"multiple\"/> The series was broadcast in various parts of [[Asia]] as well as the [[United States]], garnering much popularity and establishing Rain as a [[Hallyu]] star.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2007/10/398_11884.html|title=10 Hallyu Stars|date=August 14, 2007|website=The Korea Times}}</ref>  His performance in the drama won him the Best Actor award at the [[KBS Drama Awards]].<ref name=success /> Rain next starred in action romance drama ''[[A Love to Kill]]'' opposite [[Shin Min-ah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.donga.com/List/3/all/26/244151/1|title=From Singer to Combat Sports Fighter, an Actor Is Born|date=October 27, 2005|website=The DongA Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Rain made his big-screen debut in romantic comedy film ''[[I'm a Cyborg, But That's OK]]'', directed by [[Park Chan-wook]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2006/01/04/2006010461006.html|title=Rain to Star in Park Chan-wook's Much-Awaited 'Cyborg'|date=January 4, 2006|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> The film won the Alfred Bauer Award at the 57th [[Berlin International Film Festival]],<ref>Jeanine Tan, [http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/moviesfeatures/view/262675/1/.html Oldboy director cast Rain for his sex appeal but it's okay], ''Channel News Asia'', March 8, 2007. Retrieved March 24, 2008.</ref> and was selected as the opening film for the [[Hong Kong International Film Festival]]. Rain was nominated for and won the Best New Actor award at the 43rd Baeksang Arts Awards.<ref>[http://www.asianpopcorn.com/default.asp?Display=617 The 43rd Baeksang Awards Winners Are...], ''Asianpopcorn''. Retrieved on March 24, 2008</ref>\n\n=== 2008\u201313: Hollywood ventures ===\nIn 2008, he starred in his first English-language film, the [[Wachowskis]]-directed ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]'', where he played Racer Taejo Togokahn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/05/17/2007051761015.html|title=Rain Lands Part in Hollywood Movie|date=May 17, 2007|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> He then made his starring role debut in ''[[Ninja Assassin]]'' (2009), as the main character Raizo. ''Ninja Assassin'' was directed by [[James McTeigue]], and produced by [[Joel Silver]] and the [[Wachowskis]].<ref name=rain>{{cite journal | first=Darcy | last=Paquet | url=https://www.variety.com/index.asp?layout=festivals&jump=story&id=1061&articleid=VR1117980866&cs=1 | title=Rain falls on 'Ninja Assassin' | journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=February 13, 2008 | accessdate=May 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/11/14/2009111400259.html|title=Rain Returns as a Killer in New Hollywood Movie|date=November 14, 2009|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> The project was inspired by the ninja scenes featured from ''Speed Racer'', in which Rain had impressed the Wachowskis with his portrayal as a fighter.<ref>{{cite journal | first=Nicole | last=Sperling | url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2008/04/ninja-assassin.html | title=Wachowski Brothers getting underway on 'Ninja Assassin' | journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=April 28, 2008 | accessdate=May 20, 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503022624/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2008/04/ninja-assassin.html | archivedate=May 3, 2008 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> For his first Hollywood lead role in ''Ninja Assassin'', Rain trained alongside stuntmen for six hours a day, over six months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/11/398_55151.html|title=Rain Fueled by Fury for Ninja Assassin|date=November 9, 2009|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> He won the [[2010 MTV Movie Awards#Biggest Badass Star|Biggest Badass award]] at the [[2010 MTV Movie Awards]] for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20100607000415|title=Rain gets \u2019Biggest Badass Star\u2019 award|date=June 7, 2010|website=The Korea Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Rain returned to the small screen after five years with [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] action drama ''[[The Fugitive: Plan B]]'', in which he plays a young, rich and cunning Korean private investigator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20100927000704|title=Comeback kids amp up TV thriller|date=September 27, 2010|website=The Korea Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/4446|title=Rain says done lifetime\u2019s worth of running for \"Fugitive\"|date=September 27, 2010|website=10Asia}}</ref> This was followed by a leading role in the aviation film ''[[R2B: Return to Base]]'', which was released in August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/11453|title=Rain\u2019s \"R2B: Return to Base\" ready to glide next month|date=July 17, 2012|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that Rain would appear alongside [[Bruce Willis]], [[Jason Patric]], and [[John Cusack]] in the film ''[[The Prince (2014 film)|The Prince]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-korean-star-rain-joins-660061|title=South Korean Star Rain Joins Bruce Willis, John Cusack in 'The Prince'|date=November 26, 2013|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> Filming took place in the United States, including in [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rain to Head to Hollywood Next Week to Meet with Movie Producers|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/56094/rain-might-star-in-another-hollywood-movie/|website=Mwave|accessdate=January 16, 2014}}</ref> The film premiered in select theaters in 2014, and was also released as video on demand.\n\n=== 2014\u201316: Success in China ===\nRain made his small-screen comeback after four years in [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]'s musical drama ''[[My Lovely Girl]]'' (2014), opposite [[Krystal Jung|Krystal]] of [[F(x) (band)|f(x)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140828001051|title=Rain and Krystal make romance in drama|date=August 28, 2014|website=The Korea Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140915000877_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=\u2018My Lovely Girl\u2019 blends K-pop eye-candy and romance|date=September 15, 2014|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\nHe also starred in a [[Chinese language|Chinese]] [[romance film]], ''[[For Love or Money (2014 film)|For Love or Money]]'' alongside [[Liu Yifei]]. The film, which is Rain's Chinese film debut, premiered in November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2014/03/04/97/0200000000AEN20140304006900315F.html|title=S. Korean singer Rain to debut in Chinese film industry|date=March 4, 2014|website=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3230&blbdComCd=601006|title=Rain and LIU Yifei Melodrama Opens in Chinese Theatres|date=November 20, 2014|website=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Rain started filming for his first Chinese drama ''[[Diamond Lover]]'', co-starring [[Tiffany Tang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/11/11/2014111101783.html|title='Rain' to Star in Chinese Soap|date=November 11, 2014|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\nThe drama premiered in July 2015 and achieved huge success, earning high ratings throughout its 24-episode run and reaching 3.3 billion views online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/08/386_184752.html|title=Rain's Chinese drama gains popularity|date=August 13, 2015|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201508131310284150258_2|title=Rain\u2019s \u2018Diamond Lover\u2019 hits 3.3 billion views|date=August 13, 2015|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\nRain next starred in the [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] drama ''[[Please Come Back, Mister]]'', which began airing in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20151228000967|title=Lee Min-jung, Rain to star in new TV series|date=December 28, 2015|website=The Korea Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/12/135_193894.html|title=Rain returns to small screen|date=December 23, 2015|website=The Korea Times}}</ref>\nIn May 2016, Rain was cast alongside [[Victoria Song]] in the Chinese drama ''Endless August''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=117&aid=0002760145|script-title=ko:\ube44, \ube45\ud1a0\ub9ac\uc544\uc640 \u4e2d \ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\ud314\uc6d4\ubbf8\uc559' \uc8fc\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815|trans-title=Rain And f(x)\u2019s Victoria To Headline New Chinese Drama|website=Naver|date=May 6, 2016|publisher=My Daily|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017\u2013present: Comeback to Korea ===\nIn March 2017, Rain was cast in the movie ''[[Uhm Bok-dong (film)|Uhm Bok-dong]]'' based on a true story that took place during the Japanese colonial rule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170418000583|title=Rain, Kang So-ra to star in \u2018Uhm Bok-dong\u2019|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|author=Jie Ye-eun|date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He starred as the real-life cyclist hero [[Uhm Bok-dong]] alongside [[Kang So-ra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?blbdComCd=601006&seq=4247&mode=VIEW|title=Rain Sets Big Screen Comeback with KANG So-ra in Period Sports Drama|date=April 6, 2017|website=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Rain was cast in JTBC's action drama ''[[Sketch (2018 TV series)|Sketch]]'' as a detective.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/kwave/2018/03/06/3001000000AEN20180306006200315.html|title=Rain, Lee Dong-gun cast for cop series 'Sketch'|date=March 6, 2018|website=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201803061124281970711_2|title=Lee Dong-gun, Rain to star as investigators in \u2018Sketch\u2019|date=March 6, 2018|website=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Rain was cast in MBC drama ''[[Welcome 2 Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/07/24/2019072400899.html|title=Rain Set to Appear in New TV Series Next Month|date=July 24, 2019|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry and image==\n[[File:KoreAm June 2007 cover.jpg|thumb| Rain on the cover of ''[[KoreAm]]''{{'}}s June 2007 issue]]\n\n===Music===\n\n====Styles, lyrics and themes====\nSince his debut, Rain has primarily been influenced by [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[pop music|pop]], with \"Bad Guy\" and \"How to Avoid the Sun\" being categorized as the former, while \"Cassiopeia\" and \"Lack of Space\" are closer to the latter. By the release of ''It's Raining'', Rain, along with [[Park Jin-young]], began incorporating [[hip hop music|hip hop]] into his sound beginning with the title track.\n\nEarly in his career, most of Rain's material was handled by JYP for many years along with other songwriters and sometimes, Rain. After departing [[JYP Entertainment]], Rain began writing more of his material with other songwriters on [[J. Tune Entertainment]]. Thematically, many of Rain's songs deal with the subjects of love and heartbreak in the case of \"I Do\" and \"Love Story\". On some occasions, it can be personal (\"Can't Get Used to It\", \"My Way\"), hedonistic (\"Rainism\", \"Touch Ya\"), or celebratory (\"Hip Song\", \"Free Way\").\n\n====Voice type====\nRain's vocal range can be classified in the [[tenor]] range. His voice can be described as smooth yet husky in songs such as \"Love Story\", \"Love Song\", \"Nan\" and \"I Do\". Having been influenced by American R&B, he uses both [[vibrato]] and [[falsetto]] in many of his songs as well as incorporating [[rapping]] into songs like \"What's Love\". Rain maintains strong stance against [[lipsync]]ing during his live performances.\n\n====Influences====\nIn terms of singing and dancing, Rain has been influenced by [[Michael Jackson]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]] and [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/04/arts/music/korean-superstar-who-smiles-and-says-im-lonely.html|title=Korean Superstar Who Smiles and Says, 'I'm Lonely'|date=February 4, 2006|website=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Image===\nRain is considered a 'world star' due to his popularity, not only in [[South Korea]] and [[Japan]], but throughout [[Asia]], [[Europe]] and [[North America]] with fans in countries like [[China]], [[Singapore]], [[Thailand]], [[Canada]] and [[United States]]. Much of his popularity is attributed to his various acting roles (varying from television like ''[[Full House (2004 TV series)|Full House]]'' to indie films like ''[[I'm a Cyborg, But That's OK]]'' to blockbusters like ''[[Ninja Assassin]]''). Before landing his role in ''[[Speed Racer]]'', he had expressed the desire to expand beyond the Asian market when he stated in an interview, \"The reason I am active in Japan, Hong Kong, China and around Asia is that I want to succeed here and then go even more international...I would really like to see, is a top Asian artist emerge strongly from the Asian market, and then go on to succeed in the U.S. market.\"<ref name=cnn>{{cite web |archivedate=December 14, 2005|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2005-12-14/world/talkasia.rain.script_1_hong-kong-chinese-fans-concerts/2?_s=PM:WORLD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051214010101/http://articles.cnn.com/2005%2D12%2D14/world/talkasia.rain.script_1_hong%2Dkong%2Dchinese%2Dfans%2Dconcerts/2?_s%3DPM%3AWORLD| title=Rain Talkasia Transcript | website=CNN | date=December 14, 2005 |url-status=dead| accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRain's appeal to all demographics has made him one of Korea's highest paid celebrities by endorsers with an asking price of $1 \u2013 1.5 million USD per endorsement.  Over the years, he endorsed brands such as [[Hyundai Group|Hyundai]], [[Lotte (conglomerate)|Lotte]], [[KB Card]], [[Pizza Hut]], Thailand dairy company [[Dutch Mill]], Chinese pastry Fu Mu Cakes, [[Pantech]], [[LG Electronics]], [[SK Telecom]] and [[Pepsi]]. Rain has even done songs to tie-in with endorsement deals. \"Still Believe\" was used as both an ad and a music video for [[BMW]] Korea's \"Meet the Truth\" campaign with appearances by Rain as well as [[Park Jin-young|JYP]]. \"Memory in My Hand\"  and \"Any Dream\" were used in campaigns for [[Pantech]] and [[Samsung]], respectively, in China.\n\nWith his booming popularity throughout the world, he has been deemed a \"cultural ambassador\" as he has represented South Korea in inter-Asian musical events and has appeared in a [[Thai language|Thai]] published textbook.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201205301003_7335&nowPage=1 | title=Super Junior, Rain, Big Bang, & 2PM Appear in Thai Textbooks | date=May 30, 2012 |website=Mnet | accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n\n===Six to Five===\nSix to Five was Rain's first clothing line, since it also was his dream to become a fashion designer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/01/01/2009010161002.html|title=Workaholic Rain Branches Out into Fashion|date=January 1, 2009|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> It was launched on December 23, 2008 and was followed by a \"fashion show\u2013launch party\u2013mini-concert\" to introduce \"Six to Five\".  He designed and modeled for the clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2008/11/398_34598.html|title=Stars Delve Into Fashion, Beauty|date=November 18, 2008|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> The label \"Six To Five\" is described by Rain as the idea of having an extra sense (i.e. from five senses to six), and is also said to represent his birth date, 6/25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-launches-six-to-five-fashion-line-17435.html|title=\nRain Launches Six to Five Fashion Line|date=December 29, 2008|website=Hancinema}}</ref> The line was discontinued and the online mall closed by the end of 2010.\n\n===J. Tune Entertainment===\nIn November 2007, Rain told the Korean media that he had left JYP Entertainment and started his own entertainment company, J. Tune Entertainment (formerly known as Rainy Entertainment). He was scheduled to be [[CEO]] of the company, but told the media that he still kept in touch with his mentor and long-time trainer [[Park Jin Young]]. J. Tune Entertainment's subsidiary, J. Tune Camp debuted [[MBLAQ]], an all-boy group, in October 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/09/398_52149.html|title=Rain to Reveal New Boy Band, 5-Member MBLAQ|date=September 20, 2009|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> Rain actively participates in MBLAQ's music, either composing, writing, producing or choreographing dance routines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent9&idxno=2009092208480775082|title=Idol group MBLAQ to debut at Rain's concert|date=September 22, 2009|website=10Asia}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Park Jin-Young announced that J. Tune Entertainment would be merged with [[JYP Entertainment]]. It has become the largest shareholder in J. Tune Entertainment, and it is viewed as a strategic alliance between the two companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2930260|title=JYP Entertainment becomes J. Tune\u2019s biggest shareholder|date=December 30, 2010|accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/12/28/2010122800550.html|title=Rain to Return to JYP Entertainment|date=December 28, 2010|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\n===R.A.I.N. Company===\nOn September 7, 2015, Rain announced through his Facebook page that he had decided to not renew his contract with [[Cube Entertainment]]. After much speculation due to his departure from Cube, Rain's official website announced he had created his own one-man agency.<ref name=\"The Korean Times\"/> In setting up the agency on a U.S.-based system, his Chinese activities will be managed by H Entertainment and Jason Jang while his American agency will still be WME. His music activities will be handled by longtime manager Kim Yong Bae while his acting venture will handled by Park Jong Sun.\n\n===Humanitarian work===\nFrom 2005 to 2007, Rain donated money to have 50 drinking water wells and playgrounds built in [[Cambodia]]. He began taking up causes related to children by participating in the Love Photography Exhibition to help find adoptive parents for children in government care, donating a percent of his 2006 and 2007 World Tour concert proceeds to children orphaned by [[AIDS]] and participating in the Green Ribbon Hope Walking Campaign to raise funds for prevention and to help find missing children. Due to his work, he was appointed World Vision HIV/AIDS Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldvision.org.sg/st_campaign2.php|title=Pop Superstar RAIN Speaks Out on HIV/AIDS as World Vision HIV/AIDS Ambassador|website=World Vision Singapore|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070207054244/http://worldvision.org.sg/st_campaign2.php|archivedate=February 7, 2007}}</ref> In recent years, Rain has been an advocate for environmental protection going as far as to volunteer in the Taean oil spill cleanup and donate 300 million won for clean water and clothing for the residents in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/rain-donates-to-taean-cleanup-12106.html|title=Rain Donates to Taean Cleanup|date=January 17, 2008|website=The Korea Times}}</ref> In 2009, Rain was involved with [[MTV EXIT]], a campaign against human trafficking in Asia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2007/10/398_12386.html|title=MTV, Rain Campaign Against Human Trafficking|date=October 23, 2007|website=The Korea Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtvasia.com/shows/enslaved-an-mtv-exit-special/|title=Enslaved: An MTV EXIT Special|website=MTV Asia|language=en-sg|access-date=January 31, 2017}}</ref> Over the years, he has performed at concerts for various charitable causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hancinema.net/top-stars-gather-to-support-underprivilged-african-children-33244.html|title=Top Stars Gather To Support Underprivilged African Children|date=September 15, 2011|website=KBS World}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nOn his World 2007 tour, his scheduled concerts in [[Shanghai]], [[Toronto]], [[San Francisco]], and [[Hawaii]] were canceled, followed by the last concert in [[Los Angeles]]. The last event at the [[Staples Center]] was canceled only two hours prior to opening: Rain's producer blamed the situation on financial problems of the local promoter, while the local promoter blamed Wellmade STAR M calling them too \"incompetent to handle the situation\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Pop Singer Rain Cancels L.A. Concert |url=http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200707/200707020009.html |work= The Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=July 21, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703230704/http://english.chosun.com/w21data/html/news/200707/200707020009.html |archivedate=July 3, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2009, a federal jury in Honolulu found that Rain, his former management agency JYP Entertainment, and two other promotion companies were guilty of breaching a contract and defrauding [[Honolulu, Hawaii|Honolulu]] promoter Click Entertainment for $2 million (originally just over $1 million) after the Hawaii concert was canceled and the promoters were not refunded the $500,000 licensing fee.<ref name=\"legal suit filed\">{{cite news | first= | last= | title=Local promoters sue Rain over canceled concert | date=June 21, 2007 | work= Honolulu Advertiser|url= http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2007/Jun/21/br/br7430568912.html |  pages = | accessdate = June 21, 2007 }}</ref> Rain and JYP were ordered to pay $2.4 million each in punitive damages, $1 million for damages related to the fraud, and $2.3 million for breach of contract.<ref name=\"legal suit award\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-rain-trial-031909-2009mar19-story.html|title=Jury rules against South Korean star for $8M|last=SONG|first=JAYMES|date=March 19, 2009|work=The Associated Press|accessdate=March 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA separate lawsuit filed by promoters Wellmade STAR M was dismissed by a South Korean court on January 28, 2010. Judge Bae Kwang-Kuk ruled in favor of Rain and blamed the plaintiff for poor preparations surrounding the canceled U.S. tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2010/01/28/rain_cleared_in_u_s_concert_dispute_ |title=Rain Cleared In U.S. Concert Dispute |date=January 28, 2010 |work=Star Pulse |accessdate=June 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312004155/http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2010/01/28/rain_cleared_in_u_s_concert_dispute_ |archivedate=March 12, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010, Rain and other J. Tune Creative shareholders were accused of embezzling money from the company by a fabric manufacturing company. The company claimed they suffered financial losses. Rain and the shareholders were acquitted of the charges in December of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2930470|title=Rain cleared of embezzlement and fraud allegations|date=January 4, 2011|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> He was re investigated in September 2011 after a discrepancy was found, but was later acquitted again in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2941104|title=Rain to face reinvestigation for alleged shareholder swindle|date=September 5, 2011|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/article/39187 |title=Rain Acquitted of Malpractice Charges |date=June 24, 2013 |work=Mwave|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRain fulfilled his mandatory military service from October 2011 until July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/10/12/2011101200619.html|title=\"Teardrops Fall as Rain Enlists in Army\"|work=The Chosun Ilbo|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=October 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/07/05/2013070501054.html|title=Rain Set to Be Discharged from Military Next Week|date=July 5, 2013|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> He was named the top marksman of the 5th Infantry Division boot camp,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/11/07/2011110700675.html|title=Rain Named Top Marksman at Boot Camp|date=November 7, 2011|work=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> and was chosen as the assistant instructor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/11/09/2011110900933.html|title=Rain Chosen as Assistant Instructor at Army Boot Camp|date=November 9, 2011|work=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> He was appointed promotional ambassador by the Military Manpower Administration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/04/12/2012041201349.html|title=Rain Named Promotional Ambassador for Military|date=April 12, 2012|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> and appeared in a documentary about the defense industry entitled \"Defense Report 2012\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/04/19/2012041900832.html|title=Rain to Demo Army Guns on New TV Chosun Documentary|date=April 19, 2012|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Rain confirmed that he was dating actress [[Kim Tae-hee]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Kim Tae-hee Admits to Dating Rain|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/01/02/2013010200670.html|accessdate=January 2, 2013|newspaper=The Chosun Ilbo|date=January 2, 2013}}</ref> which then caused an investigation into whether his dating had broken military rules during his mandatory military service.<ref>{{cite news|title=South Korean singer Rain in military service row|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20887128|accessdate=July 2, 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=January 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/1481633/k-pop-star-rain-under-fire-for-allegedly-breaking-military-rules|title=K-Pop Star Rain Under Fire for Allegedly Breaking Military Rules|date=February 1, 2013|website=Billboard}}</ref> The couple married on January 19, 2017, after five years of dating.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2017/01/17/71/0200000000AEN20170117006751315F.html|title=Rain announces marriage with longtime girlfriend, actress Kim Tae-hee|work=Yonhap News Agency|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/01/20/2017012001032.html|title=Rain, Kim Tae-hee Wed in Private Ceremony|date=January 20, 2017|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\nOn October 25, 2017, Kim gave birth to their first child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201710251522242851498_2|title=Rain, Kim Tae-hee welcome first daughter|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2017/10/688_238220.html|title=Rain, Kim Tae-hee become parents of 'beautiful princess'|date=October 25, 2017|website=The Korea Times|access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> She gave her birth to their second child on September 19, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:'\ube44\u2665' \uae40\ud0dc\ud76c \uce21 \"\uc624\ub298 \uc624\uc804 \ub458\uc9f8 \ub538 \ucd9c\uc0b0, \uc0b0\ubaa8\u00b7\uc544\uae30 \ubaa8\ub450 \uac74\uac15\"(\uc804\ubb38)[\uacf5\uc2dd]|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/09/19/2019091901032.html|website=The Chosun Ilbo|publisher=Chosun Ilbo Company|accessdate=September 22, 2019|language=Korean|date=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Rain discography}}\n\n===Korean studio albums===\n* 2002: ''[[Bad Guy (album)|Bad Guy]]''\n* 2003: ''[[Rain 2]]''\n* 2004: ''[[It's Raining (album)|It's Raining]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Rain's World]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Rainism]]''\n* 2014: ''[[Rain Effect]]''\n\n===Japanese studio albums===\n* 2006: ''[[Eternal Rain]]''\n\n==Tours==\n* 2005: ''[[Rainy Day 2005 Tour|Rainy Day Tour]]''\n* 2006/07: ''[[Rain's Coming World Tour]]''\n* 2009/10: ''[[The Legend of Rainism Asia Tour|The Legend of Rainism Tour]]''\n* 2010: ''Rain Loves Japan Zepp Tour''\n* 2011: ''[[The Best Show Asia Tour|The Best Show Tour]]''\n* 2012/13: ''Army Concert Series (Consoltary Train)''\n* 2013: ''Story of Rain: 2013 Rain Zepp Tour''\n* 2014: ''Rain Effect China Concert Series (7 Concert)''\n* 2015/16 ''[[The Squall World Tour]]''\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ==