{"title_page": "Michael Bazyler", "text_new": "{{short description|American professor of law}}\n'''Michael Bazyler''' is an American professor of law and 1939 Society Law Scholar in Holocaust and Human Rights Studies at [[Chapman University]]. He previously taught at [[Whittier Law School]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty Profile |url=https://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/michael-bazyler |publisher=Chapman University |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> His book ''Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law'' was a 2016 [[Jewish Book Council]] winner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World   |url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/book/holocaust-genocide-and-the-law-a-quest-for-justice-in-a-post-holocaust-world |website=[[Jewish Book Council]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |last2=Tuerkheimer |first2=Frank M. |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |date=2015 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-1-4798-9924-1 |language=en}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fischel |first1=Jack |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/book/forgotten-trials-of-the-holocaust |publisher=Jewish Book Council |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=2015}}</ref><ref>Arac, Katelyn (2016) \"\u201cForgotten Trials of the Holocaust (Book Review)\u201d by Michael J. Bazyler and Frank M. Tuerkheimer,\"CanadianMilitary History: Vol. 25: Iss. 2, Article 3. Available at: http://scholars.wlu.ca/cmh/vol25/iss2/3</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meier |first1=David A. |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies |date=August 2016 |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=368\u2013371 |doi=10.1093/hgs/dcw038}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berghahn |first1=Klaus |last2=Dalton |first2=Russell |last3=Verber |first3=Jason |last4=Tobin |first4=Robert |last5=Crawford |first5=Beverly |last6=Luppes |first6=Jeffrey |title=Book Reviews |journal=German Politics and Society |date=1 June 2016 |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=84\u2013105 |doi=10.3167/gps.2016.340205}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fraser |first1=David |title=Forgotten trials of the Holocaust |journal=Holocaust Studies |date=20 May 2016 |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=456\u2013459 |doi=10.1080/17504902.2016.1187834}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World |date=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-539569-3 |language=en}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hogers |first1=Dani\u00ebl |title=Michael Bazyler, Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World |journal=Journal of Conflict and Security Law |date=2018 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=307\u2013310 |doi=10.1093/jcsl/kry007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Earl |first1=Hilary |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World Michael Bazyler |journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies |date=2019 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=282\u2013283 |doi=10.1093/hgs/dcz031}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Albrecht |first1=Lawrence G. |title=Book Reviews\u2014East West Street by Philippe Sands and Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law by Michael Bazyler |url=https://www.americanbar.org/groups/international_law/publications/international_law_news/2018/winter/book-reviews-east-west-street-philippe-sands-holocaust-genocide-law-michael-bazyler/ |website=[[American Bar Association]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Holocaust, Genocide, And The Law: A Quest For Justice In A Post-Holocaust World |url=https://clcjbooks.rutgers.edu/books/holocaust-genocide-and-the-law-a-quest-for-justice-in-a-post-holocaust-world/ |website=Criminal Law and Criminal Justice Book Reviews |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |last2=Boyd |first2=Kathryn Lee |last3=Nelson |first3=Kristen L. |last4=Shah |first4=Rajika L. |title=Searching for Justice after the Holocaust: Fulfilling the Terezin Declaration and Immovable Property Restitution |date=2019 |isbn=978-0-19-092306-8|publisher=Oxford University Press}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Wiener Holocaust Library Blog |url=https://www.wienerlibrary.co.uk/Blog?item=402&returnoffset=0 |publisher=[[Wiener Library]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michaelbazyler.com/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bazyler, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chapman University School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professor of law}}\n'''Michael Bazyler''' is an American professor of law and 1939 Society Law Scholar in Holocaust and Human Rights Studies at [[Chapman University]]. He previously taught at [[Whittier Law School]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty Profile |url=https://www.chapman.edu/our-faculty/michael-bazyler |publisher=Chapman University |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> His book ''Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law'' was a 2016 [[Jewish Book Council]] winner.<ref>{{cite web |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World   |url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/book/holocaust-genocide-and-the-law-a-quest-for-justice-in-a-post-holocaust-world |website=[[Jewish Book Council]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |last2=Tuerkheimer |first2=Frank M. |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |date=2015 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-1-4798-9924-1 |language=en}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fischel |first1=Jack |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/book/forgotten-trials-of-the-holocaust |publisher=Jewish Book Council |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=2015}}</ref><ref>Arac, Katelyn (2016) \"\u201cForgotten Trials of the Holocaust (Book Review)\u201d by Michael J. Bazyler and Frank M. Tuerkheimer,\"CanadianMilitary History: Vol. 25: Iss. 2, Article 3. Available at: http://scholars.wlu.ca/cmh/vol25/iss2/3</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meier |first1=David A. |title=Forgotten Trials of the Holocaust |journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies |date=August 2016 |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=368\u2013371 |doi=10.1093/hgs/dcw038}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berghahn |first1=Klaus |last2=Dalton |first2=Russell |last3=Verber |first3=Jason |last4=Tobin |first4=Robert |last5=Crawford |first5=Beverly |last6=Luppes |first6=Jeffrey |title=Book Reviews |journal=German Politics and Society |date=1 June 2016 |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=84\u2013105 |doi=10.3167/gps.2016.340205}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fraser |first1=David |title=Forgotten trials of the Holocaust |journal=Holocaust Studies |date=20 May 2016 |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=456\u2013459 |doi=10.1080/17504902.2016.1187834}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World |date=2016 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-539569-3 |language=en}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hogers |first1=Dani\u00ebl |title=Michael Bazyler, Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World |journal=Journal of Conflict and Security Law |date=2018 |volume=23 |issue=2 |pages=307\u2013310 |doi=10.1093/jcsl/kry007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Earl |first1=Hilary |title=Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law: A Quest for Justice in a Post-Holocaust World Michael Bazyler |journal=Holocaust and Genocide Studies |date=2019 |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=282\u2013283 |doi=10.1093/hgs/dcz031}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Albrecht |first1=Lawrence G. |title=Book Reviews\u2014East West Street by Philippe Sands and Holocaust, Genocide, and the Law by Michael Bazyler |url=https://www.americanbar.org/groups/international_law/publications/international_law_news/2018/winter/book-reviews-east-west-street-philippe-sands-holocaust-genocide-law-michael-bazyler/ |website=[[American Bar Association]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Holocaust, Genocide, And The Law: A Quest For Justice In A Post-Holocaust World |url=https://clcjbooks.rutgers.edu/books/holocaust-genocide-and-the-law-a-quest-for-justice-in-a-post-holocaust-world/ |website=Criminal Law and Criminal Justice Book Reviews |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n*{{cite book |last1=Bazyler |first1=Michael J. |last2=Boyd |first2=Kathryn Lee |last3=Nelson |first3=Kristen L. |last4=Shah |first4=Rajika L. |title=Searching for Justice after the Holocaust: Fulfilling the Terezin Declaration and Immovable Property Restitution |date=2019 |isbn=978-0-19-092306-8|publisher=Oxford University Press}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Wiener Holocaust Library Blog |url=https://www.wienerlibrary.co.uk/Blog?item=402&returnoffset=0 |publisher=[[Wiener Library]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michaelbazyler.com/ Official website]\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chapman University School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Bazyler"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Biddle", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Biddle (surname)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Thomas Biddle\n|image = Major Thomas Biddle by Thomas Wilcocks Sully and Thomas Sully, 1832, oil on canvas - National Gallery of Art, Washington - DSC09680.JPG\n|imagesize = 250px\n|caption = Major Thomas Biddle, by Thomas Wilcocks Sully and Thomas Sully, 1832\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1790|11|21}}\n|birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], \n|death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1831|8|29|1790|11|21}}\n|death_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause = Gunshot during a [[duel]]\n|resting_place = [[Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)|Calvary Cemetery]]<br>St. Louis, Missouri\n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|nationality = American\n|known_for = [[War of 1812]] hero, duel with [[Spencer Pettis]]\n|occupation = U.S. Army officer\n|spouse = Ann Mullanphy\n|children =\n|parents = [[Charles Biddle|Charles]] and Hannah Biddle.\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Biddle''' (November 21, 1790 \u2013 August 29, 1831) was an American military hero during the [[War of 1812]]. Biddle is better known though for having been killed in a [[duel]] with [[Missouri]] Congressman [[Spencer Pettis]].\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Biddle was born into the powerful [[Biddle family]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], one of ten children born to [[Charles Biddle|Charles]] and Hannah (Shephard) Biddle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8696865|title=Charles Biddle biography|publisher=Find A Grave website|date=April 28, 2004|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> \nHis father Charles was a Revolutionary War officer and vice-president of the [[Supreme Executive Council of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania]]. Two of Thomas' brothers, [[James Biddle (commodore)|James]] and [[Biddle House (Mackinac Island)|Edward]], had served in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]], while brother [[John Biddle (Michigan politician)|John]] was a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] officer before becoming an early mayor of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. Older brother [[Nicholas Biddle (banker)|Nicholas Biddle]] was president of the [[Second Bank of the United States]].<ref name=\"Christensen\">Christensen, Lawrence O., ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'', University of Missouri Press, 1999, pg.66</ref>\n\n==War of 1812 and post-war==\nDuring the War of 1812, Thomas Biddle was commissioned, as a captain of artillery, under [[Zebulon Pike]]. He saw action, at [[Fort George, Ontario|Fort George]] and [[Battle of Stoney Creek|Stoney Creek]] and was wounded, at [[Olde Fort Erie|Fort Erie]]. Biddle was wounded again at the [[Battle of Lundy's Lane]], where he distinguished himself by capturing the only British cannon seized in the clash. It would later be preserved and displayed in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Christensen\"/> In 1814 Biddle was [[Brevet (military)|brevetted]] to the rank of Major and became an aide for [[George Izard]]. In 1819, he accompanied the [[Yellowstone Expedition]] up the Missouri River to the vicinity of present-day [[Omaha, Nebraska]].<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/historyboonecou00unkngoog History of Boone County, Missouri]'' (1882).  St. Louis: Western Historical Company.  Retrieved 2016-01-05.  pp. 141\u201342.</ref><ref>Carlson, Gayle F., John R. Bozell, and Robert Pepperl (2004).  [http://www.nebraskahistory.org/archeo/pubs/Engineer%20Cantonment.pdf ''The Search for Engineer Cantonment''.]  [http://www.nebraskahistory.org/index.shtml Nebraska State Historical Society.]  Retrieved 2015-12-04.  p. 6 of PDF.</ref>  In August, 1820 he was transferred to [[St. Louis, Missouri]] where he served as U.S. Army [[paymaster]].\n\nOn September 1, 1823 Thomas Biddle married Ann Mullanphy, daughter of Missouri's first millionaire, [[John Mullanphy]]. Now serving as the director of the St. Louis branch of the Bank of the United States, the Biddles were financially well-off and at the peak of young St. Louis society, often hosting lavish dinner parties for business and political luminaries. It was their involvement in local politics that would have deadly consequences, however.\n\n==Politics==\nWhat transpired on August 26, 1831 had its roots many months earlier. Missouri's [[Jacksonian democracy|Jacksonian Democrats]], led by [[Thomas Hart Benton (politician)|Senator Thomas Hart Benton]], engaged in a number of debates, during the 1830 Congressional election season, that saw many fiery speeches, on issues of banking, currency stability, and western land use. During one of those speeches, Congressman [[Spencer Darwin Pettis]], a Benton acolyte, harshly criticized Biddle's brother Nicholas, President of the [[Second Bank of the United States]].<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/archives/education/dueling/political-duels.asp|title=Biddle-Pettis Duel|publisher=Missouri Secretary of State website|year=2007|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA war of words soon ensued, in the St. Louis press, in the form of letters to the editor. In one such letter, Thomas Biddle called Pettis, ''\"a dish of skimmed milk\"'', to which Pettis responded by questioning Thomas Biddle's manhood.<ref name=\"Christensen\"/> Pettis was reelected to U.S. Congress, in November, 1830, but the feud between the two refused to die. Things escalated dramatically on July 9, 1831, when Biddle heard that an ill Pettis was resting in a St. Louis hotel. Biddle attacked Pettis in his room, beating him severely with a cowhide whip until other hotel guests intervened.\n<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\">{{cite web|url=http://archiver.rootsweb.com/th/read/ROOTS/2003-10/1065765205 |title=Fatal Meeting Between Major Biddle and Spencer Pettis |publisher=Sedalia Democrat, Sedalia, Missouri |date=March 4, 1877 |accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFearing that he might be attacked again during his recovery, Congressman Pettis had Major Biddle arrested on a peace warrant. At the court proceedings, Pettis attempted to draw a pistol with the intention of shooting Biddle, but was restrained by friends. At this, Biddle stated that he would promptly accept any challenge that the Congressman cared to issue.<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\"/> After sufficient time to recover from the beating, on August 21, 1831, Congressman Pettis challenged Biddle to a duel, which indeed was promptly accepted. As the challenged party, Biddle was allowed to choose the weapons and distance. Being nearsighted, Major Biddle chose pistols at the unusually close distance of five feet.<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\"/> This meant that each man would take at most one or two steps before turning to fire, with their pistols perhaps even overlapping, depending on arm length. In short, it was suicidal and seen as a ploy by some observers and later historians to make Pettis back down and thus lose the affair of honor without bloodshed.<ref>Christensen, Lawrence O., ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'', University of Missouri Press, 1999, pg.68</ref>\n\n==Affair of honor and death==\nAt five p.m. on August 27, 1831, Thomas Biddle and Spencer Pettis, along with their seconds, Major Benjamin O'Fallon and Captain Martin Thomas respectively, met on [[Bloody Island (Mississippi River)|Bloody Island]], a small sandbar located in the [[Mississippi River]] between St. Louis and the [[Illinois]] shore. Dueling was illegal in both states, but authorities tended to turn a blind eye to this neutral ground. As large crowds watched from the St. Louis riverfront, Biddle and Pettis obeyed the commands to step, turn, and fire. When the smoke cleared, both men had fallen with mortal wounds.<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\"/> Before being carried off the island, both men were overheard to forgive each other for the altercation. Congressman Spencer Pettis died the next day, while Major Biddle lingered on until August 29. Both men were buried with full honors, eulogized for choosing death before dishonor.<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\"/> The funerals for both men were said to be the largest ever held in St. Louis in the 19th century. As a war hero, Thomas Biddle was first buried with full military rites at [[Jefferson Barracks Military Post|Jefferson Barracks]] in St. Louis, until some years later when he was disinterred to be buried with his wife in a crypt at [[Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)|Calvary Cemetery]] in St. Louis.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biddle, Thomas}}\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:Duelling fatalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Biddle family|Thomas]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:1790 births]]\n[[Category:1831 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Biddle (surname)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Thomas Biddle\n|image = Major Thomas Biddle by Thomas Wilcocks Sully and Thomas Sully, 1832, oil on canvas - National Gallery of Art, Washington - DSC09680.JPG\n|imagesize = 250px\n|caption = Major Thomas Biddle, by Thomas Wilcocks Sully and Thomas Sully, 1832\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1790|11|21}}\n|birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], \n|death_date = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|1831|8|29|1790|11|21}}\n|death_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause = Gunshot during a [[duel]]\n|resting_place = [[Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)|Calvary Cemetery]]<br>St. Louis, Missouri\n|resting_place_coordinates = \n|nationality = American\n|known_for = [[War of 1812]] hero, duel with [[Spencer Pettis]]\n|occupation = U.S. Army officer\n|spouse = Ann Mullanphy\n|children =\n|parents = [[Charles Biddle|Charles]] and Hannah Biddle.\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Biddle''' (November 21, 1790 \u2013 August 29, 1831) was an American military hero during the [[War of 1812]]. Biddle is better known though for having been killed in a [[duel]] with [[Missouri]] Congressman [[Spencer Pettis]].\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Biddle was born into the powerful [[Biddle family]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], one of ten children born to [[Charles Biddle|Charles]] and Hannah (Shephard) Biddle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8696865|title=Charles Biddle biography|publisher=Find A Grave website|date=April 28, 2004|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> \nHis father Charles was a Revolutionary War officer and vice-president of the [[Supreme Executive Council of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania]]. Two of Thomas' brothers, [[James Biddle (commodore)|James]] and Edward, had served in [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]], while brother [[John Biddle (Michigan politician)|John]] was a [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] officer before becoming an early mayor of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]. Older brother [[Nicholas Biddle (banker)|Nicholas Biddle]] was president of the [[Second Bank of the United States]].<ref name=\"Christensen\">Christensen, Lawrence O., ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'', University of Missouri Press, 1999, pg.66</ref>\n\n==War of 1812 and post-war==\nDuring the War of 1812, Thomas Biddle was commissioned, as a captain of artillery, under [[Zebulon Pike]]. He saw action, at [[Fort George, Ontario|Fort George]] and [[Battle of Stoney Creek|Stoney Creek]] and was wounded, at [[Olde Fort Erie|Fort Erie]]. Biddle was wounded again at the [[Battle of Lundy's Lane]], where he distinguished himself by capturing the only British cannon seized in the clash. It would later be preserved and displayed in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Christensen\"/> In 1814 Biddle was [[Brevet (military)|brevetted]] to the rank of Major and became an aide for [[George Izard]]. In 1819, he accompanied the [[Yellowstone Expedition]] up the Missouri River to the vicinity of present-day [[Omaha, Nebraska]].<ref>''[https://archive.org/details/historyboonecou00unkngoog History of Boone County, Missouri]'' (1882).  St. Louis: Western Historical Company.  Retrieved 2016-01-05.  pp. 141\u201342.</ref><ref>Carlson, Gayle F., John R. Bozell, and Robert Pepperl (2004).  [http://www.nebraskahistory.org/archeo/pubs/Engineer%20Cantonment.pdf ''The Search for Engineer Cantonment''.]  [http://www.nebraskahistory.org/index.shtml Nebraska State Historical Society.]  Retrieved 2015-12-04.  p. 6 of PDF.</ref>  In August, 1820 he was transferred to [[St. Louis, Missouri]] where he served as U.S. Army [[paymaster]].\n\nOn September 1, 1823 Thomas Biddle married Ann Mullanphy, daughter of Missouri's first millionaire, [[John Mullanphy]]. Now serving as the director of the St. Louis branch of the Bank of the United States, the Biddles were financially well-off and at the peak of young St. Louis society, often hosting lavish dinner parties for business and political luminaries. It was their involvement in local politics that would have deadly consequences, however.\n\n==Politics==\nWhat transpired on August 26, 1831 had its roots many months earlier. Missouri's [[Jacksonian democracy|Jacksonian Democrats]], led by [[Thomas Hart Benton (politician)|Senator Thomas Hart Benton]], engaged in a number of debates, during the 1830 Congressional election season, that saw many fiery speeches, on issues of banking, currency stability, and western land use. During one of those speeches, Congressman [[Spencer Darwin Pettis]], a Benton acolyte, harshly criticized Biddle's brother Nicholas, President of the [[Second Bank of the United States]].<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/archives/education/dueling/political-duels.asp|title=Biddle-Pettis Duel|publisher=Missouri Secretary of State website|year=2007|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA war of words soon ensued, in the St. Louis press, in the form of letters to the editor. In one such letter, Thomas Biddle called Pettis, ''\"a dish of skimmed milk\"'', to which Pettis responded by questioning Thomas Biddle's manhood.<ref name=\"Christensen\"/> Pettis was reelected to U.S. Congress, in November, 1830, but the feud between the two refused to die. Things escalated dramatically on July 9, 1831, when Biddle heard that an ill Pettis was resting in a St. Louis hotel. Biddle attacked Pettis in his room, beating him severely with a cowhide whip until other hotel guests intervened.\n<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\">{{cite web|url=http://archiver.rootsweb.com/th/read/ROOTS/2003-10/1065765205 |title=Fatal Meeting Between Major Biddle and Spencer Pettis |publisher=Sedalia Democrat, Sedalia, Missouri |date=March 4, 1877 |accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFearing that he might be attacked again during his recovery, Congressman Pettis had Major Biddle arrested on a peace warrant. At the court proceedings, Pettis attempted to draw a pistol with the intention of shooting Biddle, but was restrained by friends. At this, Biddle stated that he would promptly accept any challenge that the Congressman cared to issue.<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\"/> After sufficient time to recover from the beating, on August 21, 1831, Congressman Pettis challenged Biddle to a duel, which indeed was promptly accepted. As the challenged party, Biddle was allowed to choose the weapons and distance. Being nearsighted, Major Biddle chose pistols at the unusually close distance of five feet.<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\"/> This meant that each man would take at most one or two steps before turning to fire, with their pistols perhaps even overlapping, depending on arm length. In short, it was suicidal and seen as a ploy by some observers and later historians to make Pettis back down and thus lose the affair of honor without bloodshed.<ref>Christensen, Lawrence O., ''Dictionary of Missouri Biography'', University of Missouri Press, 1999, pg.68</ref>\n\n==Affair of honor and death==\nAt five p.m. on August 27, 1831, Thomas Biddle and Spencer Pettis, along with their seconds, Major Benjamin O'Fallon and Captain Martin Thomas respectively, met on [[Bloody Island (Mississippi River)|Bloody Island]], a small sandbar located in the [[Mississippi River]] between St. Louis and the [[Illinois]] shore. Dueling was illegal in both states, but authorities tended to turn a blind eye to this neutral ground. As large crowds watched from the St. Louis riverfront, Biddle and Pettis obeyed the commands to step, turn, and fire. When the smoke cleared, both men had fallen with mortal wounds.<ref name=\"archiver.rootsweb.com\"/> Before being carried off the island, both men were overheard to forgive each other for the altercation. Congressman Spencer Pettis died the next day, while Major Biddle lingered on until August 29. Both men were buried with full honors, eulogized for choosing death before dishonor.<ref name=\"Biddle-Pettis\"/> The funerals for both men were said to be the largest ever held in St. Louis in the 19th century. As a war hero, Thomas Biddle was first buried with full military rites at [[Jefferson Barracks Military Post|Jefferson Barracks]] in St. Louis, until some years later when he was disinterred to be buried with his wife in a crypt at [[Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)|Calvary Cemetery]] in St. Louis.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biddle, Thomas}}\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:Duelling fatalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Biddle family|Thomas]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:1790 births]]\n[[Category:1831 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Calvary Cemetery (St. Louis)]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n", "name_user": "Bigturtle", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Biddle"}
